rchy, Middle Eastern societies were both hospitable as well as hostile to National Socialist ideology during the 1930s and 1940s. By focusing on Arab and Turkish reactions to German anti-Semitism and the persecution and mass-murder of European Jews during this period, this expansive collection surveys the institutional and popular reception of Nazism in the Middle East and North Africa. It provides nuanced and scholarly yet accessible case studies of the ways in which nationalism, Islam, anti-Semitism, and colonialism intertwined, all while sensitive to the region’s political, cultural, and religious complexities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aAntisemitismxHistoryx20th centuryxGermany. 0aAntisemitismxPublic opinion. 0aAntisemitismzAfrica, North. 0aAntisemitismzGermanyxPublic opinion. 0aAntisemitismzMiddle East. 0aArabsxAttitudes. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xPublic opinion. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945). 0aNational socialismxHistoryx20th centuryxGermany. 0aNational socialismxPublic opinion. 0aPublic opinionzAfrica, North. 0aPublic opinionzMiddle East. 0aTurksxAttitudes. 7aHISTORY / Holocaust.2bisacsh  aaccessible.  aanti semitism.  aarab and turkish reactions.  acase studies.  acolonialism.  aexpansive collection.  agerman anti semitism.  aislam.  amiddle east and north africa.  amiddle east reception of nazism.  amiddle east.  amiddle eastern societies.  anationalism.  anorth africa.  anuanced and scholarly.1 aAchcar, Gilbert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBashkin, Orit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErgene, Boğaç A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErgene, Boğaç A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 